Third Point, Loeb’s Hedge Fund, Urges Amgen to Consider a Breakup


				By Michael J. de la Merced			
October 21, 2014 4:03 pm
October 21, 2014 4:03 pm







PhotoDaniel Loeb, founder of the hedge fund Third Point.Credit Steve Marcus/Reuters

Related Links


Documents: Third Point’s Investor Letter (PDF)


With corporate breakups on Wall Street’s mind, one of the biggest activist hedge fund managers around thinks the maneuver could prove helpful for the drug giant Amgen.
Third Point, the hedge fund run by Daniel S. Loeb, suggested on Tuesday that the drug maker should consider splitting itself into two businesses: a faster-growing entity whose products require heavy amounts of research spending, nicknamed GrowthCo; and a slower-growing company with more mature products that can afford to pay out a hefty dividend, known as MatureCo.
After the news, shares in Amgen were up nearly 5 percent in late afternoon trading on Tuesday, valuing the company at more than $107 billion.
Corporate spinoffs have come into vogue in recent years as companies — some under pressure from shareholders eager for higher returns — have slimmed down their operations by shedding noncore assets. Corporations including eBay, DuPont and Procter & Gamble have all announced, to varying degrees, breakup plans that would leave them running more focused businesses.

 
Spinoffs are particularly attractive, because they are likely to incur far lower taxes than an outright sale of a division might. 
In the case of Amgen, such an idea isn’t new. Mr. Loeb acknowledged that the idea for splitting the drug maker in two was first proposed by Geoffrey Porges, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein. Nevertheless, such a move would make sense, given that separating the two businesses could make it easier to focus on developing new drugs and attracting executive talent.
“A separation of Amgen into MatureCo and GrowthCo would likely be very well received by investors,” Mr. Loeb wrote in his firm’s latest letter to its own investors. “Importantly, however, we believe that a separation would not just be good for shareholders, but that it is a more effective way of running each business.”
By Mr. Loeb’s reckoning, a breakup could yield significant results. Given its current corporate self-help plan, Amgen appears set to improve its stock’s valuation to $189 a share by the end of 2016. But if the company splits itself in two, the hedge fund manager contends, the company’s stock could rise to almost $249 a share — or 81 percent higher than where the stock closed on Monday.
The hedge fund manager added in his letter that he had run the ideas by Amgen’s management team, led by its chief executive, Robert A. Bradway, and found those executives “receptive” to his suggestions.
In a statement, Amgen said that it appreciated hearing from investors, including Third Point, and that its management team continued to study ways to improve the company’s stock price. Executives plan to provide an update on their strategic plan on Oct. 28.
While Third Point is trying to goad Amgen into breaking itself up, it has exited from another investment where it urged a corporate split. Mr. Loeb disclosed that his hedge fund has sold off its investment in Sony, more than a year after urging the Japanese electronics giant to partially spin off its American entertainment business. 
Though Sony rejected the suggestion — “regrettably,” according to Mr. Loeb — the hedge fund noted that the company made several moves that have helped lift its fortunes. Among them were cost-cutting, getting out of the personal computer business and improving its television unit’s profitability. 
The hedge fund magnate pointed to what he said was the most important result of his so-called constructivist campaign: Third Point generated a nearly 20 percent return on its investment before selling out.





